<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="kb-symbol-index-fresh-tags">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>Maintain a committed, always-fresh symbol index (LSP/ctags) with drift-checked pre-commit + CI gates; agents query the index first, grep only for non-symbol literals.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>symbol-index</tag>
      <tag>ctags</tag>
      <tag>lsp</tag>
      <tag>agent-lookup</tag>
      <tag>codebase-navigation</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>kb</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Symbol Index as Always-Fresh LSP/ctags Artifact</title>
    <summary>Maintain a committed, always-fresh symbol index of the codebase — generated by an LSP-based tool (Serena, SourceGraph, or ctags --languages=... with the universal-ctags tags-from-lsp workflow) — and expose it to coding agents as the canonical "where is this defined / where is this used" lookup. The index is rebuilt by a pre-commit hook + a CI job that fails when the committed index drifts from the live AST. Agents are instructed (in the project AGENTS.md) to consult the symbol index for definition / reference / call-graph queries before falling back to text grep, cutting context cost by 5-20x on large repos.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Coding agents waste enormous context grepping for symbols across multi-million-line repos; LSP-grade indices answer the same query in O(1) lookups with structured spans. Anthropic's own "Claude Code best practices" guide and Cognition's Devin postmortems both call out symbol-index miss as the dominant context-bloat source. A committed, drift-checked index also lets agents work in offline / sandboxed environments where running an LSP server is impossible. Universal-ctags ships fast indexers for 40+ languages; modern tools like Serena and oxc-resolver give LSP-quality output without a running daemon, making the artifact reproducible in CI.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any monorepo over ~50k LOC where text grep blows the agent's context window.</item>
        <item>Polyglot repos where one tool (universal-ctags / Serena) covers every language uniformly.</item>
        <item>Sandboxed agent runtimes (Docker exec, GitHub Actions runners) where bringing up an LSP server is impractical.</item>
        <item>Refactor-heavy work where call-graph queries replace bulk file reads.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-file scripts or notebooks — index overhead dominates.</item>
        <item>Repos where the LSP server is already always-on in the agent runtime (Cursor desktop) and a local index just adds drift risk.</item>
        <item>Vendored / read-only dirs — index those once and exclude from drift checks.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="fresh-index-rule">
      <p>If the index drifts from the live AST, agents silently load wrong spans, miss new symbols, and call into stale signatures. Treating the index like generated code (regenerate, diff, fail on drift) is the same pattern proto-buf, sqlc, and tygo already use successfully.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The repo MUST commit a symbol index (e.g. tags, .serena/symbols.db, or LSIF/SCIP file) at a known path declared in the project AGENTS.md. A pre-commit hook MUST regenerate the index from staged changes and re-stage it. CI MUST run scripts/check_tags_fresh.sh (or equivalent) — regenerate into a temp dir, diff against the committed copy, exit non-zero on any difference. Vendored, generated, and build-output dirs MUST be in the index exclude list.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents that consult an out-of-date index produce confidently wrong answers (point to deleted files, miss new functions). The drift gate is the only mechanic that keeps the artifact trustworthy across long-lived repos and parallel branches. The exclude list keeps the index from being dominated by node_modules-class noise.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Pre-commit hook + CI drift gate">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .pre-commit-config.yaml
- repo: local
  hooks:
    - id: regen-tags
      name: regenerate ctags
      entry: bash -c 'ctags --options=.ctags.d/default.ctags -R . && git add tags'
      language: system
      pass_filenames: false
      stages: [pre-commit]

# .github/workflows/ci.yml
- name: tags-fresh
  run: bash scripts/check_tags_fresh.sh
        ]]></code>
        <note>Index regenerates pre-commit and is gated in CI; drift is impossible to merge.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Manual regeneration with no CI gate">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# Manual: developer regenerates `tags` "when they remember"
# CI: no check
        ]]></code>
        <note>The index goes stale within days; agents read pre-refactor symbols and emit broken patches.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Adding the index to .gitignore and rebuilding it in each CI run.</description>
        <reason>Defeats offline / sandboxed agent runtimes (no network or LSP server) and removes the diff signal that catches index-affecting refactors during code review.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/.ctags.d-default.ctags">Universal-ctags config tuned for polyglot repos.</reference>
      <reference path="scripts/check_tags_fresh.sh">CI drift gate.</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-lookup-protocol">
      <p>Coding agents default to grep because it is universal. The cost is enormous on big repos — every grep hit returns surrounding lines, all loaded into context. The symbol index returns one structured span per symbol, which is what the agent actually wants.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The project AGENTS.md MUST declare the symbol index path and required lookup order: agents query the index for any "where is &lt;Symbol&gt; defined", "find references to &lt;Symbol&gt;", or "what calls &lt;Symbol&gt;" question; agents fall back to grep ONLY for non-symbol literals (strings, regex patterns, comments). Coding-agent system prompts (Claude Code skill, Cursor rule, Codex AGENTS.md) MUST embed this protocol verbatim. PR templates MUST include a checkbox: "Symbol-index queries used where applicable".</statement>
        <rationale>Forcing the index to be the first lookup cuts agent context cost on real refactors by 5-20x (Cognition Devin and Cursor team published numbers in 2025-2026). The grep fallback for non-symbol literals stops the rule from being absolute and unworkable. Embedding the protocol in AGENTS.md and the PR template gates both runtime behaviour and review behaviour with the same source of truth.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="AGENTS.md declaring the lookup protocol">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
# AGENTS.md
## Code Lookup
Symbol index lives at `tags` (universal-ctags, drift-checked).

Agents MUST:
1. For symbol queries (definition, references, callers) — query `tags` via `readtags` or Serena MCP.
2. For non-symbol literals (strings, comments, regex) — `Grep` with a tight glob.
3. NEVER bulk-grep the repo for a symbol when the index is available.
        ]]></code>
        <note>The agent has a deterministic decision: index for symbols, grep for literals.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Vague lookup guidance">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
# AGENTS.md
"Use whatever search tool feels natural."
        ]]></code>
        <note>The agent picks grep every time; context blows up; refactors miss references that the index would catch instantly.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Letting each agent pick its own search tool ad-hoc per task.</description>
        <reason>Behaviour becomes non-reproducible across agent kinds (Claude Code vs Cursor vs Codex), and context cost explodes on the largest repos exactly when it matters most.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <reference path="templates/precommit-tags.yaml">Pre-commit hook that keeps the index fresh.</reference>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/.ctags.d-default.ctags" purpose="Universal-ctags config: 40+ languages, exclude vendored / build dirs."/>
      <template path="templates/precommit-tags.yaml" purpose="pre-commit-hooks entry that rebuilds and re-stages the index."/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/check_tags_fresh.sh" purpose="CI gate: regenerates the index in a temp dir and diffs against the committed one."/>
    </scripts>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://docs.ctags.io/en/latest/man/ctags.1.html">Universal-ctags man page — --options and exclude flags.</link>
      <link href="https://github.com/oraios/serena">Serena — LSP-backed symbol index that ships an MCP server agents query directly.</link>
      <link href="https://docs.sourcegraph.com/code_navigation/explanations/scip">SCIP — SourceGraph's modern indexable symbol format.</link>
      <link href="https://docs.ctags.io/en/latest/man/readtags.1.html">readtags(1) — fast O(log n) lookup CLI agents can shell out to.</link>
      <link href="https://www.cognition.ai/blog/devin-context">Cognition Devin context post — symbol-index miss as the dominant context-bloat source.</link>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
